{
  "text": "Subjects were initially screened for S. haematobium infection. In Kawama village, where houses are close to each other, the Kawama primary school was used as the screening site. In Milopa village, where houses are spaced many kilometers apart, an outreach health center and two cereal-grinding mill stations where villagers take their maze grain for grinding were used as screening sites. Urine filtrations were performed on three consecutive days between 9:00 AM and 3:00 PM for eggs/10 mL using Nuclepore (Whatman International Limited, Maidstone, England) membranes (12 m). The membranes were reused after each urine examination after a rigorous cleaning process to rid them of any S. haematobium ova using a technique described by Mshinda and others. [CITATION_1] Ten percent of the urine samples were re-examined by a second technician.",
